\paperw12240\paperh15840\margl1800\margr1800\margt1440\margb1440\deftab1195\f0\fs24\cf0
\pard\plain \tx1123\tx1685\tx2246\tx2794\tx3355\tx3917\tx4478\tx5040\tx5602\tx6163\tx6725\fi720\ri-720\sl288\slmult1\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 It shouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t have been possible to keep white robes clean in a journey through the desert, but the Vessels managed it. They\u8217\'92d refined some secret oil bath which held the cloth strong against the smear of sand and sweat. The men themselves were not as robust. They unraveled the moment they saw the courtyard skewered with pilgrim poles. Half cried out at the smell, a few vomited, the rest became enraged.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle was the only level head amongst them. He barked orders with clean diction, orders assiduously planned for such an event. He reorganized his men into squares, formed a squad of the literate to anatomize the scene, dispatched messengers to the nearest outpost, and sent scouts ahead into the Pass. The scouts were to give tongue if they found signs of anything unusual. His final order was to send the squeamish away to seek the spring which fed the Goree\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s tower. He had them look for foraging opportunities as well, for a return journey. Moto muttered something about how there wouldn\u8217\'92t be a return journey, implying death, and Pyetle laughed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We are no pilgrims,\u8221\'94 he said with a grin. \u8220\'93We will kill whatever dwells in these mountains.\u8221\'94 And with that same presumptive smile he ducked into a huddle of his commanders and began to scheme. It was only then that it became clear that this Hrkan scribe actually intended to honor his side of the bargain and make an attempt to understand what had happened here.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri was made to sit inside the tower\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s tunnel while the rest of the small army busied themselves with killing time. One tall fellow with a tilted chin and rebellious teeth took bets on who of the Ayramun would be executed first. Others tended to their aching feet. Some sized Ayram up while they debated amongst themselves who could take him. A circle of hungry smiles dreamed out loud, in a competitive sort of way, about women. All this disgusted one sanctimonious fellow who admonished his fellows about respect for the dead. His sermon fell on deaf until one of the pilgrims gave a gurgled moan, and that snapped the entire Hrkan host back into a deep and persistent gloom.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Those Hrks who moved amongst the poles were careful to steer clear of Elrahet. She stood amongst those pilgrims like a crow, back bent with a peevish beak, herald of a day of death with the sun already high in the sky. She grumbled unintelligible things. Her grumbling got so uncomfortable to hear that Pyetle paused his scheming to wonder if he and his were being cursed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If something is on your mind,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said as he broke from his huddle, \u8220\'93Then say out it out loud, that the sun might hear!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Elrahet went silent. The distance between her and Pyetle was only twenty yards, but when she turned and scowled it seemed she was as far away as the moon. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Don\u8217\'92t worry,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said, \u8220\'93I know better than to hold an old witch\u8217\'92s enthusiasms against her. Speak your mind, or stop brooding.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Elrahet\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s scowl hardened. \u8220\'93If you value your lives,\u8221\'94 she said to all those gathered, \u8220\'93you will begin your hunt before the hand is through.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle stroked his beard. His long fingers bore silver rings, with each band marking several years of study in logic, rhetoric, and calculation. Yes, his scribal fingers sparkled with intellect as they pulled insight out at the root. How could such a man, with such education, misjudge anything?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 He said, grandly, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I would be a poor mirror for the Lordship if I were to blindly trust a witch.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then open your eyes,\u8221\'94 Elrahet scolded. \u8220\'93If you dither now, do leave a bevy of men behind. You shall need their hands to tender your carcass to the knackers.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle thought for a moment, seemed to consider the ravaged body of a nearby pilgrim, but before he could make up his mind, one of his scouts came sprinting out the depth of the Pass. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The scout\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s bearing was wild and his panicked breathing wracked his chest. He pushed past every intervening Hrk to gave a hushed report which only Pyetle\u8217\'92s coterie could hear. One rumored word whipped through the crowd to reach Mandri\u8217\'92s ear: demons.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Thus, the hunt was on.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri moved somewhere in the middle of it, sandwiched between two loaves of angry Hrkan men. On they went, first up the gently rising wagon path which led into the Pass proper. After the first bend, Pyetle turned his column into a sinuous canyon which cut through the northern face. Inside this chasm was a stair which bent up and disappeared into a fissure which seemed to split the entirety of the Pass\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s northern plateau in two. This opening was hardly wider than Mandri\u8217\'92s shoulders, yet every Vessel in front barreled into it without so much as a stutter step.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 This fissure was a spindly squeeze of stone, with layers of red upon red, and all of it bent by the ages into dramatic, sweeping forms. These fluctuating walls bracketed a thin, winding strip of blue sky above. Such was the height and swerve that direct sunlight could not touch the mush of sand and fallen rock that was the floor. It was all quite beautiful, yet the Hrks marched at speed, and they marched for good long while, such that the sun had time to hop over the streamlet of sky above.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 After a hand or two, or perhaps three, the way belled out into a valley whose slopes bulged with piles of stone for a length of the chasm had collapsed to open it up. To the left, towering above the rubble, was the Goree\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s tallest plateau, stretching beyond vision. Above that plateau was the blazing, latter-day sun. Below, sheltering in the shadows of the larger stones, were stands of Hrkwhite Vessels. Seb was among them.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Almost there,\u8221\'94 she said upon seeing Mandri\u8217\'92s pained expression approach.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Almost where?\u8221\'94 he asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Before Seb could answer, a pox-scarred soldier got between them and pushed Seb onwards.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 From here, the march stretched out into a trickle. As daylight dimmed, the way turned again into a scramble which led steeply upwards. When Mandri finally lifted his eyes from the ankle-twisting rocks, he found himself standing on top of a grand plateau. The Hrkan advance was stretched out along it, cohesion lost, for pods of threes to fives trailed behind ones and twos, all of them scurrying towards a distant, dizzying staircase that led up to a higher plateau. Halfway through a tired groan, Mandri realized that those stairs, that climb, that monumental stump of rock, it was all a building.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 As far as buildings went, it looked like a massive clay saucepot set upside down. It looked like a child had scrawled geometric designs into its curving wall; diamonds, squares, and circles were everywhere joined together to make abstract faces; animal faces, demonic faces, faces inside of faces. An oval taller than ten men demarcated the edges of a fox\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s gape. The nostrils of the fox were the eyes of a hawk, and the beak of the hawk was the tooth of the fox and also the skull of a mouse. This parade of creation wrapped all the way around the pottish structure like a belt.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri had trouble thinking through his astonishment. And then the trail of hrkwhite specks climbing the structure\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s steps invested him with a sense of scale\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 it was enormous.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 It was a wonder.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 He\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d never seen its like.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 All the man-made wonders get their place in Hrkan art, and so by rights this building should have been included. The Hrkan brush is especially attracted to the monuments of Outland tribes, for the glories of the conquered vitalize the glory of the conqueror. This saucepot would have been a bright jewel in a Lordly crown, and that\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s not even accounting for how the evening sun painted the stone with flame. The lack of its account in Hrkan art could only be explained by ignorance\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the Lords did not know of it. If they had, the building would have been reduced to a painting a long, long time ago. And the Hrks would have an easy time capturing it now, for it appeared to be abandoned. If it were a living temple, the wind would be smearing incense smoke into the sky\u8217\'92s purpling hues while dour voices chanted Old Jandri hymns with all the guttural intensity of a lizard litter brushed with the scent of a snake. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri rushed along. When he stepped up the foot of the structure\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s stair and looked up, all his weariness escaped him. Even his aches and pains were afraid of this place. They wanted nothing to do with those three-hundred-something steps, each steep and uneven, like layers of melted wax. A dark stain climbed up them. Mandri guessed that up above, some unattended bucket of oil had spilled, found a groove, and then streamed all the way down to the bottom. If it wasn\u8217\'92t oil, well, it could be any number of other substances. Perfumed wine, red berry brine, or ink. It could be slurried excrement; a temple that large had to drain out somewhere. Odd that they\u8217\'92d have it running out the front door. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 But he knew it was blood. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Because of course it was blood.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 There weren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t any people where people were expected to be.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Blood explained the stain, and it explained the general unease creeping under his skin. It explained why his knees trembled and why, as he crested the final stair and stepped onto the temple\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s forecourt, why he felt the urge to flee. And that wasn\u8217\'92t the end of it, for the curving wall\u8217\'92s innumerable faces\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 those jackals, bats, and sows\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 they all collapsed into a swirl of lines just above a tall entrance arch, giving the impression that all the world was being sucked into that dark interior. The building itself was a carnivorous beast, for many of those swirling faces were stained by that same dark substance which dripped down the stairs. Yes, that grand entrance arch was a blood-stained maw. Perhaps it had eaten the Greskalun. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 More explanatory power.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Form up!\u8221\'94 Pyetle barked, his voice a little slimmer in this thinner mountain air.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A Vessel grabbed Mandri by the neck and arranged him alongside the assembling Hrkan squares. When they were all formed up atop that table of rock, Pyetle began a formal review. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 His resolute eye ticked from face to face. He seemed upset. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri risked a sheepish glance to try and puzzle out what was fouling Pyetle\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s mood, and of course, there was Elrahet, a hunched mist of a woman in this sea of hrkwhite robes. She and Pyetle stared each other down in some arcane contest of wills.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Sir!\u8221\'94 A Vessel shouted. \u8220\'93There is someone in there!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle spun around and hurried up to the temple\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s blood-stained threshold. He drew his sword as if to do battle with the building, then peered inside its yawning mouth. After a wary inspection, he shouted, \u8220\'93Fetch a torch!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A particularly eager Vessel unshouldered his pack, then pulled from it a handy stick with a resin-soaked wrap. He knapped sparks onto a bundle of tinder, encouraged a meager flame with a few blown kisses, then set the torch\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s head ablaze. He then offered it to Pyetle.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You lead,\u8221\'94 Pyetle commanded.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pride swelled the Vessel\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s chest. He strolled towards the mouth of the temple, torch held high. Pyetle kept close, sword at the ready. When they disappeared into the temple\u8217\'92s interior, a whole square of Vessels spilled in behind.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A few garbled words echoed back out. After an uneasy finger of waiting, the Vessels nearest the entrance slackened into unconcern.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It smells like piss!\u8221\'94 one them complained.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93All piss smells stale,\u8221\'94 said the other.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Then from the darkness, Pyetle bellowed, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Fetch the pokes!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  In short order, Ayram, Moto, Mandri, Seb, Elrahet, and a gagged Moteah were forced inside.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The temple\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s entrance hall was a grand, colonnaded affair, as wide as a Lord\u8217\'92s barge, thrice as long, and at least four times Mandri\u8217\'92s height. In the middle of this torchlit dimness, dug out into the floor, was a large octagonal fire pit filled to the brim with white ash. Wind had tossed some of this ash around the room, frosting the floor. On the other side of this pit, facing those gathered, was a man sitting cross-legged.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle was standing over him, waving his torch back and forth.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The man did not move.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Robed in green and splattered in ash, this man sat slumped, arms folded into his robe, chin-tucked as if sleeping. The only bit of visible skin was his nose which peeked out from under the fall of his long black, ash splattered hair.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Prolly dead,\u8221\'94 Seb marked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You think so?\u8221\'94 said Moto dryly.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle ordered more torches made, and when these flared up they revealed a floor rich with the scattered remains of all manner of small creatures\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 thin boned lizard legs, bats, birds, mice, and plenty of beetle shells too. This was the den of a beast. All were quieted, all save Elrahet, whose heavy robes turned}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  these gruesome scraps over as s}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 he waddled right up to that cross-legged figure.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Move aside,\u8221\'94 she grumbled.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle reluctantly gave her distance.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 When she was ready, she poked the sitting man with her cane.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The man\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s head slumped onto his shoulder. His hair fell away from his cheek. She poked again, and he fell onto his side. The thump of his impact kicked up a cloud of ash. \u8220\'93Dead,\u8221\'94 she declared, and then she rubbed the man\u8217\'92s green robe between her gnarled fingers. \u8220\'93Viggy wool,\u8221\'94 she remarked. \u8220\'93The raiment of a prince. This was Greskal\u8217\'92s son.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle spread the light of his torch onto several more resin-strapped sticks and handed them out to his men. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Is this who who we\u8217\'92ve come to hunt?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No,\u8221\'94 said Elrahet. \u8220\'93Though he might have been. See there\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94 She pointed towards a dark lump on the floor about an arm\u8217\'92s length behind the dead prince. That lump had a mop of dark hair and a human ear. It had a neck, and attached to that neck were a few links of spine. What mangled flesh there was appeared to have been munched on.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes darted between this horror and green robed prince. \u8220\'93You suggest that this man }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 ate}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  the other?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Elrahet\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s natural scowl hardened. \u8220\'93Do not judge this boy. HisSpark was brighter than yours.\u8221\'94 She poked around the fire pit with her cane. There she revealed, buried deeply in ash, a large stomach. Evidently the green-robed prince had cut it out at the neck and then tossed it into the fire like a lure, dragging with it the rest of his intestines. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If he had lost his battle,\u8221\'94 Elrahet said, \u8220\'93we\u8217\'92d have two Burshageets to hunt instead of one.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Burshageet?\u8221\'94 Pyetle asked, tongue toying with the unfamiliar word. But Elrahet was too busy rolling the stomach around in its ashy bed to clarify. And what a sight. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The stomach\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s pink flesh was peppered white and still sticky. When she rolled it over again, some part of it squelched and fizzled, as if it were still digesting something.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 At this, Elrahet grunted, then mumbled something unintelligible. Seh dragged the stomach closer with her cane. She knelt, drew out her black knife, and with a quick, terrible stroke, she cut the thing open. Another quick flick, and the knife\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s length levered the stomach\u8217\'92s two halves apart. Then, she peered into that stomach\u8217\'92s pit to divine the future, or, perhaps she sought the past.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri knew very little about the art of divination. He knew only that the stomach was the seat of the Spark and that the organ was subdivided into regions, each with its own special significance\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the stem, the gate, the portal vein, the sphincter, and so on. Most importantly, there were patterns in the folds of the interior lining. One could, with the right training, not only interpret the true meaning of events with those folds, but predict them altogether. But his was not a functional knowledge. He did not expect, after half a finger of silent staring, that he would understand anything here, but then the dissected stomach squirmed and burped up a puff of black smoke that spread unnaturally quick throughout the room.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 It did not take a witch to interpret this sign. All knew by way of myth what a Spark looked like when it was snuffed out of existence.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The astonished crowd of Vessels backed away from the fire-pit. Half-eaten bones crunched under their feet. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Evil!\u8221\'94 one cracking Vessel shouted, while another fell to his knees and muttered a warding prayer. A third man lowered his spear towards Elrahet with an aim to end her then and there.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, now you notice to me,\u8221\'94 Elrahet said, voice low and measured. \u8220\'93You Hrks always ignore a witch\u8217\'92s warnings until the, well listen to me now when I say this: The beast is near.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It seems to me that our quarry is dead,\u8221\'94 Pyetle countered.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No. No it is not.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I see a demon here\u8230\'85a half-demon\u8230\'85and he is dead. Though I must admit that there is more to all this than I originally suspected.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And more, still!\u8221\'94 Elrahet intoned.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri surveyed the shadows for any lurking demon that might be scenting the air with a forked tongue. He looked behind, and there, a glint of metal caught his eye. He looked closely, and yes, the torchlight teased a glinting something hanging above the temple\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s exit. He had trouble interpreting what it was until one of the torch bearing Hrks walked underneath it\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 it was an enormous golden mask of Solraheen.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 It was a rare Old Jandri relic. The facial planes were bloated with healthy fat. Long, curved lines traced the contours of the cheek and bulbous chin like tattoos. Heavy lidded eyes lent His visage a sense of serenity. Mandri was drawn to it, even if the style was long outlawed by Hrk, as it was sacrilegious to depict Solraheen\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s features so brazenly. One must not claim knowledge of such things. Only the most abstract representation, a circle, would do. Even stretching that circle into an oval so as to suggest a jaw was forbidden on pain of having to start all over again. And this mask was huge, at least two heads tall. Hrkan sacral masks could be worn, but this was much too large. When Hrkan masks were out of use, they were inset into a wall or ensconced within a small wood shrine, but this hung out in the open, mounted on a bronze plate and pillowed with opalescent lizard hides that had been polished to a sheen.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 It was a beautiful sight.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Though none of it glittered as brightly as it should. A thick layer of dust dulled its luster. Fire-lorn ash speckled His face like freckles. All this could be forgiven because there was no one to attend to Him. What could not be forgiven was how His golden skin was darkly mottled.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Tarnished.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pure gold cannot tarnish. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The Greskalun had polluted His flesh with impure metals.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 No wonder these people were missing. They deserved whatever smiting they received.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 And worse, standing at the foot of the entrance arch were two long-necked shooki jugs\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 jugs of urine. It was impossible to say for certain what this urine was for, but there was narrative proximity here which could not be ignored. Surely the Greskalun were bathing their god in their own piss to try and scrub away the tarnish. One indignity to wash away another.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They should have settled for a smaller Solraheen,\u8221\'94 Mandri mumbled.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What\u8217\'92s that?\u8221\'94 Pyetle asked from the center of the room.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A chill ran down Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s spine as everyone in the room suddenly looked to him. Thankfully, one soldier had noticed Mandri staring up at the face of Solraheen, and this man pointed out the discovery as his own. \u8220\'93A sacral mask!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 This drew the attention of several torches to the shadow of the entrance wall. The approaching light revealed a design which stirred a thrill of disbelief, for on the wall behind the golden mask, in sharp sandstone relief, were one hundred and twenty long triangles\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the overlapping rays of the sun. The number did not need to be counted for the pattern exactly matched the sigil of Hrk. The only real difference between this wall and the Hrkan design was how, the sharp points of these splayed sun-rays terminated into the mouths of worried faces. These faces were carved with such realism that Mandri actually felt repulsed by the threat of skill. He wanted, again, to flee, but the Hrks had crowded the exit.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What is this doing here?\u8221\'94 one gruff fellow sneered. His warted nose sniffled as he spoke, as even the hairs inside his nostrils were stood on end.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why should these pokes honor us?\u8221\'94 asked another.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Honor?\u8221\'94 The warted one gasped. \u8220\'93This is defilement! They mock us!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They mock Solraheen!\u8221\'94 said yet another Vessel. \u8220\'93A mask of impure gold is damnable work.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 All agreed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 One man called to tear the whole wall down, prompting another to stab the stonework with his spear. He aimed for the nose of one the light-swallowing figures, but it was the spear\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s tip which cracked instead. A shard of the blunted iron went tinging along the floor, and into the echo of tinging metal there crept a cackling laugh, shrill and deeply amused.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 All men turned to face Elrahet. So close to the floor was she, with all but her ancient face obscured by her pillowing robes, that she appeared to have reverted to some accursed larval stage.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Are you not Hrkan men?\u8221\'94 she jeered. \u8220\'93Will none of you bow to the sigil of your Lordship?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The crowd of hrkwhite cloaks were loathe to hear her speak, much less tease them.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Have your histories forgotten this place already?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She eyed them all with a cold and steady gaze. When she found Pyetle\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s questioning glare, she answered it. \u8220\'93This place is a prison.\u8221\'94 Her lips curled, and Pyetle stiffened.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The demon we hunt is imprisoned here?\u8221\'94 he asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She shook her head. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It was Solraheen who was enchained in the bowels of this place.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s brow scrunched up tight. \u8220\'93The god of all creation? Imprisoned here?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93He did escape,\u8221\'94 Elrahet clarified.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I would have bet that He did. What could possibly contain Him?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Elrahet appeared to float up to her feet. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Every mind is bound by the power of the word,\u8221\'94 she said. \u8220\'93}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Duty. Honor. Oath.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  These words bind you to this moment as readily as Solraheen was bound by the repetition of His name. If you had heard the word blossom\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This is not the time for stories,\u8221\'94 Pyetle muttered as he glared at the crumpled body of the dead Prince. Ash-splattered green wool covered the Prince\u8217\'92s wilted shoulder and twisted knee. Even for a corpse, the pose looked uncomfortable. Then his gaze turned to that black stomach still sizzling in the ash. He breathed deeply. \u8220\'93Something nearby needs killing,\u8221\'94 he said. \u8220\'93\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It does not matter where your suspicions lie, for what needs killing cannot be killed by }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 you}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 .\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Right,\u8221\'94 Pyetle mused. \u8220\'93Your quarry can only be killed by this Mazid. Well I\u8217\'92m sorry to disappoint, but unleashing him would defeat the whole purpose of our being here.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then you, and I, and every other Spark in this forsaken world will be snuffed out.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle inclined his head and drew his smirk wide. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Me and mine are more than willing to die should the Lordship require it. There is no greater service than sacrifice.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Tell me, Pyetle, how long does it take for a Burshageet\u8217\'92s stomach to swell to the size of a thundercloud? Could Mazidfire prevent that beast from consuming all the world?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Are you saying that it\u8217\'92s now or never?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Young Pyetle,\u8221\'94 Elrahet said, \u8220\'93there is no choice. You will act now, I have foreseen it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle looked to his men.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Apprehension darkened the room.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If it helps,\u8221\'94 Elrahet said, \u8220\'93Then yes\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 it is now or never.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Slate!\u8221\'94 Pyetle called, and the only Hrk in the room not wearing a headscarf stepped forward. This man, named Slate, was flat-faced with wide-set eyes and a bald, gleaming pate, presumably his namesake. He did not appear to be a thinking man. More than this, Mandri was struck by the sense that Slate\u8217\'92s blocky head could not, even in principle, be painted. His chin looked strong from from the front but was rather steep and weak from the side, while his nose was practically a wall from the front, but barely there from any other angle. With a skull so wide and flat, no two-dimensional account of him could be made. It gave him the impression of having been sculpted by a middling hand who refused to use a reference model.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle told Slate to help him choose who to send back to the tower to give a report, but this was only a pretext. He was to pick and choose which of the Vessels would die, for those who remained would journey down into this ancient prison, down to its stomach perhaps, likely never to return. Slate pointed out the shifters, the fidgeters, the men too eager for eye contact. Curiosity, too, was taken a sign of weakness, for it was well known that a confident man has no use for curiosity, he knows exactly where he stands and why.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pyetle waved all these suggestions away. He opted to send away the men with families, as well as the men who were nearing the end of their contracts. These men were gathered and dismissed until only thirty-odd Vessels remained. Pyetle kicked up a strut in front them as they condensed into tighter squares. His pace was building up to a speech.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Solraheen put you here,\u8221\'94 he said proudly, pointing to the golden mask above the entrance.  \u8220\'93He guided you all through your long lives, so that you would be standing here and now. He guided each one of you to this very moment.\u8221\'94 He paused to let the weight of this obligation settle on proud shoulders. \u8220\'93You are not unlucky to be here,\u8221\'94 he continued. \u8220\'93I would tell you to get rid of that feeling, but I know that none of you feel it. You know that you are lucky. Few chance to meet evil with the clarity that you do now. And how will you meet it? Will you charge into the dark and kill what festers there? It is easy to say, \u8216\'91Yes!\u8217\'92, but are you willing to die to kill it? I am. I am, because I will die with the luxury of knowing exactly what I\u8217\'92ll say to Solraheen when I meet Him.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What will you say?\u8221\'94 Slate asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ll say send me back, so that I can finish the job!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Slate encouraged a weak hurrah, and Pyetle swept this mild feeling up by drawing his sword.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Think of your name being nailed to the head of a demon as children parade it down the Whiteway!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Think of the women!\u8221\'94 Slate shouted.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The meaty women!\u8221\'94 Pyetle roared to a swell of heartier cheers. And with their courage half-gathered, Pyetle marched into the dark passage that was barely there in the distant end of the room.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  Mandri was forced to trudge along behind, though he did not share in any excited visions of meaty victories. It was almost like these Hrks had completely forgotten that they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d just seen a Spark dissolve into wisps of smoke.}}